stylometry: The objective of a fixed cost model is to determine if the outcome or profit is greater than the fixed costs. If it is, then they should produce the product but if it is not, the product should not even be produced. For example, a company produced shirts, shorts, pants and skirts. All the products have the same fixed cost of $20. The skirt does not make enough profit to cover the fixed cost so the company should stop producing skirts. With the set covering models, you try to minimize the number of members in set two to cover all the members in set one.
